1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,140
Okay, so we will do a quick theater today.

2
00:00:04,740 --> 00:00:09,280
Now, as a society, every
society has a problem.

3
00:00:09,460 --> 00:00:10,520
The problem is,

4
00:00:10,740 --> 00:00:14,000
how do we organize the thinking

5
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,060
of the people within our society?

6
00:00:17,540 --> 00:00:19,720
Okay, how do you create an identity?

7
00:00:23,040 --> 00:00:26,780
And in modern society,
there are three institutions

8
00:00:26,780 --> 00:00:30,820
that create a collective
identity for society.

9
00:00:31,560 --> 00:00:35,140
Okay, so the first would be what?

10
00:00:37,180 --> 00:00:38,820
Exactly, thank you, schools, right?

11
00:00:39,540 --> 00:00:44,380
So public schools, you're here to
learn about the history of China.

12
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:47,260
You're here to learn about
the politics of China, right?

13
00:00:47,420 --> 00:00:49,700
And the idea is to organize.

14
00:00:49,720 --> 00:00:50,920
Make everyone think alike.

15
00:00:51,140 --> 00:00:55,860
Or have the same basic
knowledge and worldview, okay?

16
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:59,840
What's another institution
that does this in society?

17
00:01:03,640 --> 00:01:06,480
The media, right? Okay, so mass media.

18
00:01:07,340 --> 00:01:12,020
So when you turn on the TV, when
you read a Chinese newspaper,

19
00:01:12,420 --> 00:01:14,980
it's presenting a particular worldview.

20
00:01:16,140 --> 00:01:19,380
And when you absorb this worldview,
you become more Chinese.

21
00:01:19,720 --> 00:01:22,300
Right? And what's the last institution

22
00:01:22,300 --> 00:01:27,100
that helped us form a
collective identity in China?

23
00:01:32,720 --> 00:01:34,800
Entertainment, right? Mass culture.

24
00:01:36,380 --> 00:01:39,220
This includes, you know, TV shows.

25
00:01:39,560 --> 00:01:41,240
This includes movies, okay?

26
00:01:41,420 --> 00:01:43,140
This includes books. Does that make sense?

27
00:01:43,540 --> 00:01:45,180
So through these three institutions,

28
00:01:45,440 --> 00:01:48,740
societies can create a national identity.

29
00:01:49,100 --> 00:01:53,220
And that's what we're going to do today.
And depending on your society, you create a different worldview, right?

30
00:01:53,460 --> 00:01:54,720
So in America,

31
00:01:55,020 --> 00:01:59,420
Americans would want to create
an individualistic identity.

32
00:01:59,920 --> 00:02:04,220
Whereas in China, we want to
create a collectivist identity,

33
00:02:04,560 --> 00:02:06,140
okay? So

34
00:02:06,140 --> 00:02:09,480
what I will show you
today is Greek society,

35
00:02:09,840 --> 00:02:12,640
Athenian society was doing
the same thing, okay?

36
00:02:12,820 --> 00:02:14,560
But it was doing it through theater.

37
00:02:17,280 --> 00:02:19,700
And the main function of theater
is to create a collective identity.

38
00:02:19,700 --> 00:02:25,320
And the main function of theater was to
create an identity as a democratic citizen,

39
00:02:25,680 --> 00:02:27,620
okay? Democratic citizen.

40
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:32,800
Why do we have a democracy?

41
00:02:33,200 --> 00:02:35,160
What does it mean to live in democracy?

42
00:02:35,580 --> 00:02:38,920
What is your responsibility as
a citizen to be in a democracy?

43
00:02:39,580 --> 00:02:44,700
Okay? So that's what
theater does in Athens.

44
00:02:45,720 --> 00:02:48,800
So let me give you some
background about theater.

45
00:02:48,960 --> 00:02:53,340
Okay? Theater was the form,

46
00:02:53,440 --> 00:02:55,540
the basic structure of Athenian society.

47
00:02:57,180 --> 00:03:00,200
So there are two months of the year when

48
00:03:00,200 --> 00:03:03,280
everyone went to the theater, okay?

49
00:03:03,420 --> 00:03:07,740
So once in winter and
once in the summertime.

50
00:03:08,100 --> 00:03:13,360
And they were called the
festival of Dionysus,

51
00:03:13,440 --> 00:03:15,320
okay? Dionysus was the god,

52
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:19,660
the Greek god of the
theater, of art, of culture.

53
00:03:19,660 --> 00:03:21,800
Of music, of sex, of wine.

54
00:03:22,920 --> 00:03:26,700
And so the festival of Dionysus,
there were religious elements to it.

55
00:03:27,400 --> 00:03:30,660
But it was mainly about watching theater.

56
00:03:31,240 --> 00:03:33,540
And through the process
of watching theater,

57
00:03:33,740 --> 00:03:38,660
Athenians created a national identity

58
00:03:38,660 --> 00:03:40,660
that they all believed in.

59
00:03:41,320 --> 00:03:44,920
Okay? So this happened
twice a year for one month.

60
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:46,980
And it was free for everyone.

61
00:03:47,240 --> 00:03:48,740
So it was the rich who...

62
00:03:49,640 --> 00:03:52,180
Paid for all the plays to be performed.

63
00:03:52,420 --> 00:03:54,960
And that's how the rich,
the aristocratic families,

64
00:03:55,180 --> 00:03:59,120
won favor from the people. In fact,

65
00:03:59,200 --> 00:04:02,680
Athenians considered going to theater the

66
00:04:02,680 --> 00:04:05,420
greatest birthright of being an Athenian.

67
00:04:05,560 --> 00:04:08,820
Okay? That was the privilege and
the right of being an Athenian.

68
00:04:09,400 --> 00:04:13,060
It was the highest honor in

69
00:04:13,060 --> 00:04:16,900
Athens to participate in the
festival as a playwright.

70
00:04:16,900 --> 00:04:19,640
And every festival,

71
00:04:19,800 --> 00:04:21,760
there would be two competitors.

72
00:04:22,260 --> 00:04:24,880
Okay? And they were
called the protagonist.

73
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:28,660
Okay? And antagonist.

74
00:04:29,560 --> 00:04:34,140
So today, we know that protagonist
means the hero of a novel.

75
00:04:34,500 --> 00:04:36,780
Antagonist means the villain of a novel.

76
00:04:36,920 --> 00:04:41,000
But back then, all this meant was
you were the first competitor.

77
00:04:41,320 --> 00:04:43,300
And then the antagonist
was the second competitor.

78
00:04:43,540 --> 00:04:46,880
Okay? And the entire process...

79
00:04:46,880 --> 00:04:51,260
The entire point of theater was
to promote democracy in Athens.

80
00:04:51,700 --> 00:04:54,240
And they did that through many mechanisms.

81
00:04:54,960 --> 00:04:56,180
First of all,

82
00:04:56,280 --> 00:05:00,920
whoever won the festival
was decided by popular vote.

83
00:05:01,580 --> 00:05:05,380
Okay? The entire process
of theater was democratic.

84
00:05:05,860 --> 00:05:08,560
So there were no professional
actors in Athens.

85
00:05:08,900 --> 00:05:10,500
People were selected from the

86
00:05:10,500 --> 00:05:16,020
community to act out the play.

87
00:05:16,020 --> 00:05:21,180
And everyone participated
in watching the play.

88
00:05:21,340 --> 00:05:24,120
In fact, the largest amphitheater...

89
00:05:24,120 --> 00:05:26,220
These are all outdoor theaters in Athens.

90
00:05:26,420 --> 00:05:28,200
Could hold 10,000 people.

91
00:05:28,520 --> 00:05:30,460
Okay? 10 to 15,000 people.

92
00:05:30,900 --> 00:05:34,840
The maximum population of
Athens was 50,000 people.

93
00:05:35,100 --> 00:05:39,860
Okay? So this is a huge community
event that brought everyone together.

94
00:05:40,060 --> 00:05:43,400
And they loved the theater. Um...

95
00:05:46,020 --> 00:05:48,900
The three most famous
playwrights in Athens at that

96
00:05:48,900 --> 00:05:50,860
time were Aeschylus,

97
00:05:53,940 --> 00:05:58,500
Sophocles, and Euripides.

98
00:05:58,740 --> 00:06:01,800
Okay? And these were
really playwrights, poets.

99
00:06:02,100 --> 00:06:05,360
But they were first and
foremost prophets of democracy.

100
00:06:05,900 --> 00:06:09,120
They were teachers of democracy who

101
00:06:09,120 --> 00:06:11,400
told the Athenian people,
Why do we have democracy?

102
00:06:11,820 --> 00:06:13,200
Why is democracy good?

103
00:06:13,200 --> 00:06:17,540
And how should we protect
and promote our democracy?

104
00:06:18,260 --> 00:06:20,820
Alright? So in their plays,

105
00:06:21,080 --> 00:06:23,340
the very heart and

106
00:06:23,340 --> 00:06:27,580
soul of their plays was about the
promotion of democracy in Athens.

107
00:06:27,980 --> 00:06:32,120
And these three were the most
admired of all the playwrights.

108
00:06:32,120 --> 00:06:35,180
Everyone at that time
wanted to be a playwright.

109
00:06:35,360 --> 00:06:38,860
Because that was the
highest honor in Athens.

110
00:06:39,060 --> 00:06:42,480
Okay? So to win first place
at the Festival of Dionysus,

111
00:06:42,480 --> 00:06:45,300
is like winning the Nobel
Prize in Physics today.

112
00:06:46,200 --> 00:06:49,320
Okay? So, um, what I will do now,

113
00:06:49,620 --> 00:06:53,020
is go over the most famous plays,

114
00:06:53,180 --> 00:06:56,180
so we can understand how
they promoted democracy

115
00:06:56,920 --> 00:06:58,840
through their artwork.

116
00:06:59,260 --> 00:07:01,220
But are there any questions
so far? Before I continue.

117
00:07:03,040 --> 00:07:04,420
Yes, it's an amphitheater.
Yes, it's an amphitheater.

118
00:07:06,440 --> 00:07:10,960
the theater is kind of like
a theme park in the theater.

119
00:07:10,960 --> 00:07:12,280
Yes, it's an amphitheater.

120
00:07:12,420 --> 00:07:14,880
So how did you all come together?

121
00:07:15,220 --> 00:07:19,120
How can you all come together
and do a play as an ensemble?

122
00:07:20,080 --> 00:07:22,120
Okay, so that's a great
question about acoustics.

123
00:07:22,140 --> 00:07:25,360
We call this acoustics. So how the
theater was designed was like this, okay?

124
00:07:25,540 --> 00:07:27,260
You have the stage, and then

125
00:07:27,260 --> 00:07:31,520
the theater was designed like
this, like an oval, okay?

126
00:07:32,280 --> 00:07:33,680
So in other words,

127
00:07:34,580 --> 00:07:38,920
the sound was captured in
like a cavern in a cave.

128
00:07:39,240 --> 00:07:41,040
So there was resonance. But

129
00:07:41,040 --> 00:07:44,720
obviously you were required
to shout out the words slowly

130
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:46,580
so everyone can hear, okay?

131
00:07:46,700 --> 00:07:48,580
That's the first thing. Second thing is,

132
00:07:49,460 --> 00:07:53,740
these plays were so popular,
everyone memorized the lines.

133
00:07:54,540 --> 00:07:56,820
Do you understand? So

134
00:07:56,820 --> 00:07:59,660
they already knew the
content of the plays,

135
00:07:59,860 --> 00:08:04,660
but they wanted to participate in
the community aspect of the play.

136
00:08:04,840 --> 00:08:07,160
Does that make sense?
So the two things is,

137
00:08:07,340 --> 00:08:10,100
the theater was designed in a way so that

138
00:08:10,100 --> 00:08:13,940
sound traveled very freely in the theater

139
00:08:13,940 --> 00:08:17,800
so everyone can hear, but also everyone
memorized the lines anyway, okay?

140
00:08:18,360 --> 00:08:20,680
Does that make sense?
Okay, great question.

141
00:08:20,940 --> 00:08:23,000
All right, any more
questions before I continue?

142
00:08:24,960 --> 00:08:27,540
All right, so let's talk
about Ischeles, okay?

143
00:08:27,620 --> 00:08:30,540
Because he was really the first
of the major playwrights.

144
00:08:30,580 --> 00:08:33,280
And he wrote a play called Oresteia.

145
00:08:36,760 --> 00:08:40,440
And I will explain to you the plot of
the play, the plot of the Oresteia,

146
00:08:41,100 --> 00:08:44,260
before I explain to you the meaning and

147
00:08:44,260 --> 00:08:46,760
the interpretation of the play, okay?

148
00:08:47,040 --> 00:08:50,540
So all these plays come
from Greek mythology,

149
00:08:51,340 --> 00:08:54,360
because everyone knows the mythology. And

150
00:08:54,360 --> 00:08:58,260
so what the playwrights did was, they
took material from Greek mythology

151
00:08:59,160 --> 00:09:02,620
and packaged it in a contemporary context

152
00:09:03,220 --> 00:09:05,220
to explore modern themes, okay?

153
00:09:05,620 --> 00:09:08,340
All right, so the Oresteia,

154
00:09:09,400 --> 00:09:10,920
the play is set in a place called Argos.

155
00:09:11,140 --> 00:09:13,260
And during the Mycenaean period, okay, so

156
00:09:13,260 --> 00:09:16,180
this is before the Bronze Age
collapsed, Mycenaean Greece,

157
00:09:17,020 --> 00:09:20,400
Argos was the most powerful
city in Mycenaean Greece.

158
00:09:22,060 --> 00:09:24,560
And when the king died,

159
00:09:24,900 --> 00:09:29,000
he left the throne to his
eldest son named Atreides, okay?

160
00:09:29,920 --> 00:09:35,700
But often what happens in these cases is the
younger brother refuses to accept the authority

161
00:09:36,400 --> 00:09:38,440
of the eldest, and he rebels, okay?

162
00:09:38,440 --> 00:09:43,120
So war was fought over the
Argos throne, Atreides won,

163
00:09:43,480 --> 00:09:47,860
and then his brother comes
and begs for forgiveness.

164
00:09:48,580 --> 00:09:50,940
And Atreides, being the king, says,

165
00:09:51,260 --> 00:09:54,940
you're my brother, I want to
show I'm a benevolent king,

166
00:09:55,300 --> 00:09:57,020
so I will forgive you.

167
00:09:57,180 --> 00:09:59,020
And to show that I forgive you,

168
00:09:59,180 --> 00:10:03,760
I will host for you a
banquet and a feast, okay?

169
00:10:05,020 --> 00:10:09,420
And so the younger brother is
like, he's very happy about this.

170
00:10:09,700 --> 00:10:12,040
But during the feast, before the feast,

171
00:10:12,280 --> 00:10:16,740
what Atreides does is
he kills all the sons,

172
00:10:17,440 --> 00:10:20,860
all his younger brother,
and he cooks them.

173
00:10:21,120 --> 00:10:22,420
And during the feast,

174
00:10:22,540 --> 00:10:26,240
he feeds it to his younger brother.

175
00:10:26,860 --> 00:10:29,780
And when his younger brother
finds out about this, okay,

176
00:10:29,840 --> 00:10:32,700
he dies after this, but before he dies,

177
00:10:32,780 --> 00:10:35,280
he curses Atreides and says,

178
00:10:35,420 --> 00:10:38,100
curse upon you and your house, because

179
00:10:38,100 --> 00:10:41,920
a feast is a contract between you

180
00:10:41,920 --> 00:10:43,540
and the gods, okay?

181
00:10:43,740 --> 00:10:45,280
When you hold a feast,

182
00:10:45,480 --> 00:10:48,560
you promise the gods this
feast will be peaceful.

183
00:10:49,120 --> 00:10:52,340
And so people trust you
and come and eat your food.

184
00:10:52,860 --> 00:10:56,440
So when you poison your food like this,
you are in the hands of the gods,

185
00:10:56,540 --> 00:10:58,800
so I curse you and your
entire house, okay?

186
00:10:58,840 --> 00:11:00,840
And then he dies. But before he dies,

187
00:11:01,020 --> 00:11:03,680
his son,

188
00:11:03,820 --> 00:11:07,280
Agittas, okay, Agittas, escapes, okay?

189
00:11:07,280 --> 00:11:09,800
So his only remaining son is Agittas.

190
00:11:09,900 --> 00:11:11,660
And Agittas is responsible now

191
00:11:12,080 --> 00:11:14,080
for avenging the death
of his family, okay?

192
00:11:14,800 --> 00:11:17,260
All right, so Atreides becomes king.

193
00:11:17,340 --> 00:11:21,260
He has two sons who
inherit his throne, okay?

194
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:23,880
The first is Agamemnon, who

195
00:11:23,880 --> 00:11:27,880
becomes king of Argos, and
he is the king of kings.

196
00:11:28,120 --> 00:11:32,220
He is the one who will start the Trojan
War and launch an invasion of Troy, okay?

197
00:11:32,780 --> 00:11:34,920
And his brother is Menelaus,

198
00:11:36,300 --> 00:11:38,760
who becomes the king of the Argos,
okay? And he becomes king of Sparta.

199
00:11:39,840 --> 00:11:42,960
And they both marry sisters, okay?

200
00:11:43,040 --> 00:11:44,600
They marry two sisters.

201
00:11:45,120 --> 00:11:49,640
Agamemnon marries Platamestra,
and Menelaus marries Helen, okay?

202
00:11:50,240 --> 00:11:51,600
This is important because,

203
00:11:52,280 --> 00:11:54,760
remember, Helen runs away to Troy,

204
00:11:54,880 --> 00:11:57,480
and Menelaus tells his brother,

205
00:11:57,680 --> 00:11:59,980
Agamemnon, he gets upset, and

206
00:11:59,980 --> 00:12:04,200
they agree to organize this
massive Greek army to invade,

207
00:12:04,620 --> 00:12:07,000
destroy Troy, and get Helen back, okay?

208
00:12:09,500 --> 00:12:14,140
But when they're about to set
sail for Troy, there's no win.

209
00:12:15,120 --> 00:12:19,080
And Agamemnon knows the gods
are not happy with them, okay?

210
00:12:19,200 --> 00:12:22,140
So Agamemnon consults a fortune teller

211
00:12:22,140 --> 00:12:26,060
who tells him how to win
the favor of the gods.

212
00:12:26,280 --> 00:12:30,440
He tells Agamemnon, you have
to sacrifice your daughter,

213
00:12:30,560 --> 00:12:34,400
Iphigenia. And at this point,
Agamemnon should be like,

214
00:12:35,320 --> 00:12:38,600
I'm not going to do that. I'm not
going to sacrifice my daughter,

215
00:12:38,740 --> 00:12:41,280
Iphigenia, so that I could go to Troy.

216
00:12:41,480 --> 00:12:44,560
And why do I want to go to Troy
in the first place, right?

217
00:12:45,520 --> 00:12:48,460
Helen's not my wife. It's Menelaus' wife.

218
00:12:49,080 --> 00:12:50,920
Not my problem, right?

219
00:12:51,080 --> 00:12:53,660
I should just give this up because
obviously the gods don't want me to go.

220
00:12:54,620 --> 00:12:55,980
That's what he should do.

221
00:12:56,640 --> 00:13:00,200
But instead, he's like, fine,
I'll sacrifice my daughter, okay?

222
00:13:00,280 --> 00:13:02,080
So he kills his daughter, Iphigenia.

223
00:13:02,740 --> 00:13:05,820
The wind is released from the skies,

224
00:13:05,820 --> 00:13:08,620
and he sets sail to Troy, okay?

225
00:13:08,720 --> 00:13:12,820
And we know what happens. They're there for
ten years, and they end up destroying Troy.

226
00:13:13,940 --> 00:13:17,100
Who's really pissed now?
Who's really angry now?

227
00:13:20,080 --> 00:13:22,260
Who's really angry about all this?

228
00:13:25,880 --> 00:13:27,980
Cladamestra, right? The wife of Agamemnon.

229
00:13:28,280 --> 00:13:31,820
Because their daughter has been
killed for no reason, okay?

230
00:13:33,640 --> 00:13:35,160
So Cladamestra, while

231
00:13:35,160 --> 00:13:38,240
Agamemnon is away for ten years,

232
00:13:38,440 --> 00:13:40,140
she plots her revenge.

233
00:13:40,580 --> 00:13:43,940
What she does is she finds Agittes

234
00:13:43,940 --> 00:13:45,840
and they become lovers, okay?

235
00:13:45,980 --> 00:13:50,660
And they plot how to avenge
the death of Iphigenia.

236
00:13:50,840 --> 00:13:55,280
So ten years later, when Agamemnon
comes back from Troy victorious,

237
00:13:56,420 --> 00:13:59,400
Cladamestra kills him, okay?

238
00:14:00,540 --> 00:14:04,660
And she makes Agittes now king of Troy.

239
00:14:04,660 --> 00:14:05,820
Okay,

240
00:14:12,960 --> 00:14:19,680
so now

241
00:14:19,680 --> 00:14:32,840
if you

242
00:14:32,840 --> 00:14:36,140
imagine if you imagine if
you imagine about what to do.

243
00:14:36,280 --> 00:14:37,920
So he consults Apollo,

244
00:14:38,400 --> 00:14:40,320
who is basically the god of justice.

245
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:44,920
And Apollo tells him, you are right

246
00:14:44,920 --> 00:14:47,020
and just to want to avenge your father.

247
00:14:47,600 --> 00:14:50,300
So Aristides goes back to Argos and

248
00:14:50,300 --> 00:14:52,930
he kills his mother, Cladamestra, and

249
00:14:53,500 --> 00:14:55,960
Aegisthus. And now he's king of Argos.

250
00:14:56,440 --> 00:14:59,960
The problem now is, because
he's killed his mother,

251
00:15:00,380 --> 00:15:03,060
there are these demons
called the Furies who

252
00:15:03,060 --> 00:15:07,800
come up from the underworld
and they begin to haunt him.

253
00:15:08,580 --> 00:15:09,880
They're torturing him.

254
00:15:10,300 --> 00:15:11,700
And Aristides

255
00:15:12,400 --> 00:15:17,520
becomes so tortured he
runs away from Argos.

256
00:15:17,740 --> 00:15:20,760
And he's trying to run away from the Furies,
but the Furies refused to let him go.

257
00:15:21,540 --> 00:15:23,740
And Aristides says to them,

258
00:15:23,940 --> 00:15:28,660
I killed my mother in
order to avenge my father.

259
00:15:28,780 --> 00:15:30,620
That was the runaway. So he goes back to Argos
and he says, you are right and just to do.

260
00:15:31,200 --> 00:15:32,960
And the Furies say to him,

261
00:15:33,060 --> 00:15:36,380
we are all gods.

262
00:15:37,300 --> 00:15:41,820
We are responsible for maintaining
order and structure in the universe.

263
00:15:42,200 --> 00:15:46,760
One thing that you cannot do is kill
your parents, especially your mother.

264
00:15:46,900 --> 00:15:51,380
By doing so, you are breaking
the order of the universe.

265
00:15:51,660 --> 00:15:56,400
Therefore, we will haunt you
for the rest of eternity.

266
00:15:57,380 --> 00:15:58,800
We will not let you go.

267
00:15:59,280 --> 00:16:02,160
Okay. Aristides goes talks to Apollo

268
00:16:02,160 --> 00:16:06,960
and Apollo tries to intercede
on behalf of Aristides.

269
00:16:07,120 --> 00:16:10,080
And the Furies say to
him, you are a young god.

270
00:16:10,460 --> 00:16:12,920
You are a new god. We are the old gods.

271
00:16:13,120 --> 00:16:14,380
We are much older than you are.

272
00:16:14,500 --> 00:16:16,020
We are much wiser than you are.

273
00:16:16,120 --> 00:16:18,020
You have no authority over us.

274
00:16:18,980 --> 00:16:23,500
We don't care about justice. We
don't care about the laws of men.

275
00:16:23,920 --> 00:16:26,380
We care about the laws of the universe.

276
00:16:27,060 --> 00:16:29,400
And Aristides has broken
the laws of the universe.

277
00:16:29,620 --> 00:16:31,980
Okay. So now Aristides
is in a lot of trouble.

278
00:16:32,120 --> 00:16:34,280
And so, out of desperation,

279
00:16:34,620 --> 00:16:38,940
the last thing he does is he
runs to Athens, where Athena is.

280
00:16:39,160 --> 00:16:41,760
And Athena is the goddess of wisdom.

281
00:16:42,300 --> 00:16:46,560
So Aristides tells Athena,
the goddess, his story.

282
00:16:47,100 --> 00:16:49,700
And he begs for her help.

283
00:16:49,960 --> 00:16:52,940
Okay. And Athena takes pity on Aristides.

284
00:16:53,080 --> 00:16:54,980
And she says, basically,

285
00:16:56,020 --> 00:16:58,120
I'm going to convene a jury.

286
00:16:58,300 --> 00:17:00,820
Okay. Of 500 Athenian citizens.

287
00:17:04,060 --> 00:17:07,840
And you will make your case before them.

288
00:17:07,980 --> 00:17:10,620
The Furies will make
their case before them.

289
00:17:10,720 --> 00:17:14,540
And they will decide whether
or not you are guilty.

290
00:17:15,360 --> 00:17:19,480
Okay. So both Aristides and
the Furies make their case.

291
00:17:19,700 --> 00:17:23,420
And morally speaking,
both cases are compelling.

292
00:17:23,680 --> 00:17:26,860
Okay. Because even though

293
00:17:26,860 --> 00:17:29,140
Clytemnestra killed Agamemnon,

294
00:17:29,420 --> 00:17:31,820
the fact of the matter is
Agamemnon was an asshole.

295
00:17:32,420 --> 00:17:35,920
Right? Agamemnon killed their
daughter for no particular reason.

296
00:17:36,120 --> 00:17:39,500
And then he went off to Troy and killed a
lot of people for like no reason as well.

297
00:17:39,900 --> 00:17:44,580
Okay. So both cases were very strong.

298
00:17:44,780 --> 00:17:46,140
And so at the end of the day,

299
00:17:49,060 --> 00:17:52,220
250 Athenians decided
Aristides was guilty.

300
00:17:52,380 --> 00:17:54,740
250 decided he was innocent.

301
00:17:54,840 --> 00:17:56,740
Okay. So it's what we call a hung jury.

302
00:17:56,920 --> 00:17:58,780
Okay. It was divided evenly. So what then

303
00:17:58,780 --> 00:18:01,740
happens now is Athena comes in and

304
00:18:01,740 --> 00:18:05,040
says that because you are deadlocked,
I will be the deciding vote.

305
00:18:05,140 --> 00:18:07,320
I vote in favor of Aristides.

306
00:18:07,580 --> 00:18:10,600
Okay. So now Aristides is free to go home

307
00:18:10,600 --> 00:18:13,020
and live his life in peace.

308
00:18:13,780 --> 00:18:17,120
Now the Furies say to her,
no, no, no, no, no, no.

309
00:18:17,240 --> 00:18:20,020
We don't accept your laws, Athena.

310
00:18:20,460 --> 00:18:24,960
Okay. And then Athena says to them,
fine, you guys, I'll make you a judge.

311
00:18:24,960 --> 00:18:27,780
Okay. So they accept the deal.
Okay. Right now you're a demon

312
00:18:27,780 --> 00:18:31,200
and everyone fears and hates you.

313
00:18:32,640 --> 00:18:37,760
But I will now make you stand for justice,

314
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:39,300
truth, and righteousness

315
00:18:39,740 --> 00:18:42,960
so that we, the Athenian
people, will worship you

316
00:18:42,960 --> 00:18:45,900
and admire you.

317
00:18:46,040 --> 00:18:50,400
Okay. And the Furies say, okay,
that's a pretty good deal.

318
00:18:50,520 --> 00:18:54,020
Okay. So the Furies accept this deal.

319
00:18:54,020 --> 00:18:55,980
And Aristides is allowed to go home.

320
00:18:56,360 --> 00:18:57,660
And the story ends.

321
00:18:57,880 --> 00:18:59,900
Okay. Does that make
sense? So that's the story.

322
00:19:01,020 --> 00:19:03,960
Why, so what's the
relevance of this story?

323
00:19:04,320 --> 00:19:08,960
Well, for Athens, it tells them
where democracy comes from.

324
00:19:09,200 --> 00:19:12,620
Okay. Right? Athena, the goddess herself,

325
00:19:12,780 --> 00:19:14,960
gave democracy to Athens.

326
00:19:16,380 --> 00:19:20,340
Right? But it also tells them how,

327
00:19:20,420 --> 00:19:22,620
what a tremendous gift this is.

328
00:19:22,620 --> 00:19:26,080
Because by giving the
Athenian people democracy,

329
00:19:26,620 --> 00:19:29,560
it basically gave them the power of gods.

330
00:19:30,040 --> 00:19:34,280
Right? Because when you
have these 500 jurors,

331
00:19:34,320 --> 00:19:36,700
each of them has the same power and

332
00:19:36,700 --> 00:19:39,440
authority of the god Athena herself.

333
00:19:39,840 --> 00:19:41,840
Athena can only cast one vote.

334
00:19:41,960 --> 00:19:44,800
Right? Okay.

335
00:19:44,940 --> 00:19:49,860
And so what this is telling the Athenian
people is the gods gave you democracy.

336
00:19:50,120 --> 00:19:54,740
Honor them. By taking it very seriously.

337
00:19:54,840 --> 00:19:58,700
Okay. When you vote, do so very seriously.

338
00:19:58,820 --> 00:20:01,720
Because when you vote in a good way,

339
00:20:01,840 --> 00:20:05,900
meaning you've fought very
clearly over your decision,

340
00:20:06,180 --> 00:20:09,200
then you bring justice,
truth, you bring justice

341
00:20:09,200 --> 00:20:11,480
and truth and righteousness
into the world.

342
00:20:12,480 --> 00:20:14,220
Okay? Does that make sense?

343
00:20:16,240 --> 00:20:18,820
And that's why I say Isulis
is a prophet of democracy.

344
00:20:19,160 --> 00:20:21,160
Because through this play,
he is telling the truth.

345
00:20:21,160 --> 00:20:23,480
Okay. He's telling the Athenian
people where democracy comes from,

346
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:25,760
what's important, and

347
00:20:25,760 --> 00:20:29,520
what they can do to ensure
democracy stays in Athens.

348
00:20:30,300 --> 00:20:33,380
Okay? Any questions so far about this?

349
00:20:34,740 --> 00:20:37,780
Alright? Okay.

350
00:20:37,780 --> 00:20:39,020
Let's move on to Sophocles.

351
00:20:39,220 --> 00:20:43,580
Okay? So, Sophocles wrote many plays.

352
00:20:43,760 --> 00:20:46,340
His most famous is the Oedipus Trilogy.

353
00:20:46,440 --> 00:20:50,420
Okay? Oedipus Trilogy. Now,

354
00:20:50,420 --> 00:20:55,100
you may have heard of the Oedipus Trilogy,
but I will summarize the story for you.

355
00:20:55,160 --> 00:20:57,020
Okay? So, what happened is,

356
00:20:57,240 --> 00:20:59,600
in the city of Thebes,

357
00:20:59,780 --> 00:21:03,120
a king and

358
00:21:03,120 --> 00:21:05,020
his wife, they have a young son.

359
00:21:05,320 --> 00:21:09,120
And as is the custom at that time,
they go see a fortune teller.

360
00:21:09,580 --> 00:21:11,240
And the fortune teller tells them,

361
00:21:11,440 --> 00:21:16,240
your son is going to kill you,
the father, and marry the mother.

362
00:21:16,980 --> 00:21:18,600
And the king freaks out.

363
00:21:18,620 --> 00:21:21,160
And he's like, I don't
want that. So, he tells,

364
00:21:21,420 --> 00:21:25,220
he orders his soldier to
go out and kill the baby.

365
00:21:25,720 --> 00:21:29,260
Okay? And the soldier takes the
baby, and again, it's just a baby.

366
00:21:29,480 --> 00:21:31,800
Like, you know, maybe a
few days, a few weeks old.

367
00:21:32,060 --> 00:21:35,640
He goes out in the woods. He goes out in the
woods, and he's supposed to kill the baby.

368
00:21:35,940 --> 00:21:37,680
But he's a soldier. And

369
00:21:37,680 --> 00:21:42,020
he feels it would be
dishonorable to kill a baby.

370
00:21:42,500 --> 00:21:46,220
So, what he does is, he just leaves
the baby in the woods, and runs away.

371
00:21:46,240 --> 00:21:48,520
Thinking, maybe the wolves
will come and eat the baby.

372
00:21:48,640 --> 00:21:50,140
Okay? Instead,

373
00:21:50,140 --> 00:21:54,800
a shepherd from another city
comes and finds the baby.

374
00:21:55,580 --> 00:21:57,640
And he takes care of the baby.

375
00:21:57,720 --> 00:22:00,980
Okay? He goes home. In the city, the king

376
00:22:00,980 --> 00:22:03,320
and the queen have no child.

377
00:22:03,580 --> 00:22:04,820
They have no son. They have no heir.

378
00:22:04,980 --> 00:22:10,820
Okay? So, the shepherd
presents the baby to the king.

379
00:22:10,940 --> 00:22:13,620
And the king names him Oedipus.

380
00:22:14,040 --> 00:22:16,220
And Oedipus grows up to
be a very beautiful baby.

381
00:22:16,240 --> 00:22:19,800
A very strong, very noble,
very handsome young man.

382
00:22:20,420 --> 00:22:23,820
When he is of age, he goes
and talks to a fortune teller.

383
00:22:24,280 --> 00:22:28,840
And the fortune teller tells him,
I am sorry, but you are cursed.

384
00:22:29,320 --> 00:22:32,740
You are cursed to kill your
father and marry your mother.

385
00:22:33,460 --> 00:22:36,000
So, Oedipus freaks out and
says, I don't want to do that.

386
00:22:36,200 --> 00:22:38,840
I don't want to kill
my parents who love me.

387
00:22:39,180 --> 00:22:40,980
So, he runs away from his city.

388
00:22:41,180 --> 00:22:43,280
Okay? And he's going to Thebes.

389
00:22:43,280 --> 00:22:45,200
And on the way to Thebes,

390
00:22:45,520 --> 00:22:49,560
he gets into an argument with an old man

391
00:22:49,560 --> 00:22:51,580
and his friends. And he kills all of them.

392
00:22:51,680 --> 00:22:56,280
Okay? And this old man happens to be
his real father, the king of Thebes.

393
00:22:57,780 --> 00:23:00,440
He goes into Thebes
and everyone is crying.

394
00:23:01,620 --> 00:23:04,240
And Oedipus asks what the problem is.

395
00:23:05,080 --> 00:23:08,900
And the citizens there tell
him, well, our king is dead.

396
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:10,940
And also, there's a Sphinx.

397
00:23:13,280 --> 00:23:15,780
An evil demon who is haunting us.

398
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:17,900
Okay? So,

399
00:23:17,940 --> 00:23:22,020
Oedipus volunteers to challenge
the Sphinx to a duel.

400
00:23:22,400 --> 00:23:26,380
And the Sphinx asks Oedipus a riddle.

401
00:23:26,560 --> 00:23:29,880
If Oedipus can get it right,
the Sphinx will go away.

402
00:23:30,180 --> 00:23:33,700
But if Oedipus gets it wrong,
then the Sphinx will eat Oedipus.

403
00:23:33,740 --> 00:23:35,740
Okay? And the riddle is,

404
00:23:36,080 --> 00:23:39,760
what walks in the morning with four legs,

405
00:23:40,460 --> 00:23:43,260
what walks in the
afternoon with three legs,

406
00:23:43,260 --> 00:23:47,020
and then what walks in the
evening with three legs?

407
00:23:47,400 --> 00:23:50,160
And the answer is? Yeah, man.

408
00:23:50,320 --> 00:23:53,500
Okay? So it's a very famous
riddle. Oedipus gets it right, and

409
00:23:53,500 --> 00:23:55,880
the Sphinx loses and he flies away.

410
00:23:56,040 --> 00:23:59,000
Okay? The people of
Thebes are so thankful,

411
00:23:59,320 --> 00:24:01,660
they make him king of Thebes.

412
00:24:02,180 --> 00:24:05,060
If you're king of Thebes, you
marry the queen of Thebes.

413
00:24:05,180 --> 00:24:09,300
Okay? So he's done this.
He's married his mother

414
00:24:09,300 --> 00:24:10,580
and killed his father. Okay?

415
00:24:11,360 --> 00:24:12,580
Twenty years later,

416
00:24:13,580 --> 00:24:16,080
there's a plague in Thebes.

417
00:24:16,940 --> 00:24:19,540
And Oedipus, now the king, knows

418
00:24:19,540 --> 00:24:24,220
that somehow he's angered the gods.

419
00:24:24,780 --> 00:24:26,680
So he talks to a fortune teller.

420
00:24:26,720 --> 00:24:30,240
The fortune teller tells him,
well, the gods are angry at you

421
00:24:30,240 --> 00:24:32,640
because you've killed your father and

422
00:24:32,640 --> 00:24:35,900
you've married your mother, and
you've had children of your mother.

423
00:24:36,060 --> 00:24:39,160
Okay? So all your children
are products of incest.

424
00:24:39,740 --> 00:24:41,440
So the gods are angry at you.

425
00:24:41,980 --> 00:24:45,040
So what Oedipus does,
is he blinds himself,

426
00:24:46,300 --> 00:24:48,400
and he exiles himself, okay?

427
00:24:48,500 --> 00:24:49,840
To die somewhere else.

428
00:24:49,960 --> 00:24:53,800
Okay? Now the problem now
is, who inherits the throne?

429
00:24:54,060 --> 00:24:56,860
So his eldest son is supposed
to inherit the throne,

430
00:24:57,080 --> 00:24:59,540
but he has another son, named Polyneices.

431
00:25:01,600 --> 00:25:06,000
Polyneices. Who rebels, and
he fights for the throne.

432
00:25:06,360 --> 00:25:09,340
The two brothers kill
themselves in battle.

433
00:25:09,660 --> 00:25:13,720
Okay? They kill themselves,
fight each other, and now Creon,

434
00:25:14,440 --> 00:25:16,560
who is um,

435
00:25:18,700 --> 00:25:22,900
the brother to the dead queen, the
queen has killed herself, okay?

436
00:25:23,740 --> 00:25:25,180
He now inherits the throne.

437
00:25:25,520 --> 00:25:28,880
Okay? And the first thing
he does, is announce

438
00:25:28,880 --> 00:25:32,600
that the dead king will
be given a state funeral.

439
00:25:32,860 --> 00:25:34,300
Okay? We will honor him.

440
00:25:34,480 --> 00:25:38,040
But Polyneices, who
rebelled against the king,

441
00:25:38,260 --> 00:25:41,020
and who caused all this suffering and

442
00:25:41,020 --> 00:25:44,380
misery in the world, he
will not be given a funeral.

443
00:25:44,580 --> 00:25:46,020
He will not be buried.

444
00:25:46,180 --> 00:25:49,640
And the reason why is, Greeks believe that

445
00:25:49,640 --> 00:25:54,240
only by burying the dead, can
they find peace in the afterworld.

446
00:25:54,400 --> 00:25:56,680
Okay? So it's a very serious
thing not to bury the dead.

447
00:25:58,540 --> 00:26:03,120
Antigone, who is the daughter of Oedipus,

448
00:26:03,640 --> 00:26:06,240
and the sister of Polyneices,

449
00:26:07,140 --> 00:26:10,060
she finds out about this, and
she thinks this is unjust.

450
00:26:10,060 --> 00:26:12,940
Polyneices has done a lot of bad things,

451
00:26:13,100 --> 00:26:15,760
but no one deserves this.

452
00:26:15,940 --> 00:26:19,840
Okay? So she secretly buries Polyneices.

453
00:26:20,820 --> 00:26:25,320
Creon finds out, and demands
Antigone to be arrested.

454
00:26:25,800 --> 00:26:30,500
And Creon says to her,
how dare you defy my laws?

455
00:26:30,720 --> 00:26:34,460
How dare you disrespect my orders?

456
00:26:35,080 --> 00:26:38,360
And Antigone says to him,

457
00:26:38,360 --> 00:26:41,100
your laws are unjust.

458
00:26:41,580 --> 00:26:42,780
And Creon says,

459
00:26:44,140 --> 00:26:45,880
the laws are the laws.

460
00:26:46,140 --> 00:26:48,140
Without laws, there
would be complete chaos.

461
00:26:48,700 --> 00:26:50,420
And Antigone responds by saying,

462
00:26:50,660 --> 00:26:55,360
human laws must conform to justice.

463
00:26:56,220 --> 00:26:59,400
There are these laws in the
universe that are divine,

464
00:26:59,740 --> 00:27:01,360
unwritten, and immutable.

465
00:27:01,560 --> 00:27:03,160
And we must respect these laws.

466
00:27:03,860 --> 00:27:08,300
Human laws cannot override
these laws of justice.

467
00:27:08,360 --> 00:27:10,680
And this makes Creon very angry.

468
00:27:10,880 --> 00:27:15,420
And so he sentences her to
death for disobeying him.

469
00:27:16,060 --> 00:27:17,660
The problem is,

470
00:27:17,900 --> 00:27:21,900
Antigone is the fiance of Haman,

471
00:27:22,100 --> 00:27:23,480
who is Creon's son.

472
00:27:23,680 --> 00:27:25,940
So Haman, the prince, comes and

473
00:27:25,940 --> 00:27:28,940
begs his father to relent.

474
00:27:29,620 --> 00:27:33,480
And Haman says,

475
00:27:34,360 --> 00:27:36,860
can you please forgive Antigone?

476
00:27:37,880 --> 00:27:40,840
And Creon thinks his son has betrayed him.

477
00:27:41,820 --> 00:27:44,840
Your love for Antigone has blinded you

478
00:27:45,480 --> 00:27:48,680
from seeing the truth,
from doing what is right.

479
00:27:49,600 --> 00:27:52,600
And Haman responds and says, father,

480
00:27:52,720 --> 00:27:55,120
I'm not doing this for Antigone,
I'm doing this for you.

481
00:27:55,280 --> 00:27:56,640
And the reason why is,

482
00:27:56,900 --> 00:28:01,080
the people of Thebes
fully support Antigone.

483
00:28:01,340 --> 00:28:03,200
They think she is a hero.

484
00:28:03,820 --> 00:28:08,100
They think she is just and right
to want to bury her brother.

485
00:28:08,240 --> 00:28:11,400
They think you are a tyrant, father.

486
00:28:11,980 --> 00:28:13,200
And Creon says,

487
00:28:14,580 --> 00:28:16,820
should I obey the mob?

488
00:28:17,420 --> 00:28:18,980
Should I, the king,

489
00:28:19,740 --> 00:28:21,180
listen to the mob?

490
00:28:22,100 --> 00:28:26,840
And then Haman says, no, you should
listen to what is right and just.

